I don&#39;t feel comfortable with `document.querySelectorAll(&#39;#${name}&#39;)` and I believe it is one of the reasons why it doesn&#39;t work. `querySelectorAll` will return an `HTMLCollection`, so setting `innerTest` on it does not make sense. Also, you are using an Id, so it should technically be unique on your page.

Also, I think you would benefit greatly from a &#39;dictionary&#39; object instead of a classic array:

```
let dict = {};

function upDateTable(name){
    //We check if our name exists
    if (dict[name]) {
        dict[name] += 1;
        document.getElementById(`#${name}`).innerText = myArr[name];
    } else {
        dict[name] = 1;
        //no reason to put our value in the string, we know it&#39;s always 1
        table.innerHTML += `&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;${name}&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td id=${name}&gt;1&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;`; 
    }
}
```

